    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-02-26T14:14:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-02-26T14:14:00-05:00" n="394"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d394">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 822.00/363.</note>
                <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Quito</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-02-26T14:00:00-05:14">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 26, 1914, 2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>After an hour’s fighting the prisoners at the penitentiary overcame the guards
                    this morning at 10 o’clock, took their arms and are now in control. It is
                    expected that the Government soldiers will attack them this afternoon or
                    to-morrow. The people of Quito are greatly excited and it is believed that
                    unless the Government forces succeed in the coming battle with the prisoners a
                    general plundering of the city will take place. At the request of Mrs. Plaza I
                    have received her three little sons and their nurses in the Legation and shall
                    give them and other proper applicants refuge here until the danger is over. Mrs.
                    Plaza and two daughters are at the Chilean Legation. I will take every
                    precaution to protect the Legation and its inmates from injury. The penitentiary
                    is so strongly constructed and so situated as to make it a fort overlooking the
                    city. I will keep the Department advised.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hartman</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
